COVID-19 X-ray images classification¶

Author: Yilin Xu¶

Date: Mar.12.2021¶

Introduction:¶

  • " The novel coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19), which first appeared in Wuhan, China in December 2019, spread rapidly around the world and became a global pandemic. This resulted in a devastating effect on both daily lives, public health, and the global economy. It is critical to detect the positive cases as early as possible to prevent the further spread of this epidemic and to quickly treat infected patients. The need for auxiliary diagnostic tools has increased as there are no accurate automated toolkits available. Recent findings obtained using radiology imaging techniques suggest that such images contain salient information about the COVID-19 virus. Application of advanced artificial intelligence (AI) techniques coupled with radiological imaging can be helpful for the accurate detection of this disease, and can also be assistive to overcome the problem of a lack of specialized physicians in remote villages."
  • This notebook is a replication of the DarkCovidNet model1 and transfer learning of GoogLeNet model to classify radiological images as indicative of either "COVID-19", "No Finding" and "Pneumonia" to assist in the diagnosis of COVID-19. This is an extension of the notebook published along with the paper in GitHub https://github.com/muhammedtalo/COVID-19/blob/master/DarkCovidNet%20%20for%20binary%20classes.ipynb. We use data available in Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/tawsifurrahman/covid19-radiography-database

  1. Ozturk et. al. 2020. Automated detection of COVID-19 cases using deep neural networks with X-ray. Comput Biol Med. 2020 Jun; 121: 103792. (doi: 10.1016/j.compbiomed.2020.103792).↩

Construct DarkCovidNet CNN for three classes (modified Darknet model)¶

  • Define one layer of the convolutional neural network using fastai and PyTorch
  • Each layer has one convolution, one normalization, and one activation
  • We use LeakyReLU with a negative slope of 0.1 as the activation function

ni: number of input (number of channels in the input image).

nf: number of filter.

size: kernel_size (size of the convolving kernel).

stride: skip number.

padding: amount of pixels adding to the input image.

In [7]:
def conv_block(ni, nf, size=3, stride=1):
    """
    Define 2D convolution layer
    """
    for_pad = lambda s: s if s > 2 else 3
    return nn.Sequential(
        nn.Conv2d(ni, nf, kernel_size=size, stride=stride,
                  padding=(for_pad(size) - 1)//2, bias=False), 
        nn.BatchNorm2d(nf),
        nn.LeakyReLU(negative_slope=0.1, inplace=True)  
    )

Define triple convolution layers.

In [8]:
def triple_conv(ni, nf):
    """
    Stack 2D convolution layers
    """
    return nn.Sequential(
        conv_block(ni, nf),
        conv_block(nf, ni, size=1),  
        conv_block(ni, nf)
    )

Define maxpooling with size of 2 and stride of 2 to extract most activated presence of a feature

In [9]:
 def maxpooling():
    """
    Define maxpooling method
    """
    return nn.MaxPool2d(2, stride=2)
  • Construct DarkCovidNet architecture with 17 convolution layers
  • The number of filters are gradually increased (e.g., 8,16,32)
In [10]:
def darkcovidnet_model():
    """
    Construct cnn architecture for DarkCovidNet model
    """
    model = nn.Sequential(
        conv_block(3, 8),
        maxpooling(),
        conv_block(8, 16),
        maxpooling(),
        triple_conv(16, 32),
        maxpooling(),
        triple_conv(32, 64),
        maxpooling(),
        triple_conv(64, 128),
        maxpooling(),
        triple_conv(128, 256),
        conv_block(256, 128, size=1),
        conv_block(128, 256),
        conv_layer(256, 3),
        Flatten(),
        nn.Linear(507, 3)
    )
    return model

When training Deep Learning models with Fastai it is recommended to use the fit_one_cycle() method, due to its better performance in speed and accuracy, over the fit() method. In short, fit_one_cycle() is Fastais implementation of Leslie Smiths 1cycle policy. Here we set Epoch = 40, maximum learning rate = 3e-3.

Apply sklearn stratified 5 fold cross validation¶

  • All of the images are the 256 * 256 pixels and batch size is defined as 32

  • The image data is normalized to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1

  • We will perfomr 5 fold cross validation with train and validation ratio of 4:1

  • Use fastai.vision.learner to train a randomly initialized model. Our loss function, cross-entropy loss measures the performance of a classification model as a probability value between 0 and 1. Cross-entropy loss increases as the predicted probability diverges from the actual label.

# Extract loss and accuracy values
def extract_values(data,epoch,learner,bs):
    """
    Extract loss value for train set, validation set and accuracy for validation set at end of training for each epoch 
    """
    segment = math.floor(len(data.train_ds)/bs)
    epoch_list = list(range(1,epoch+1))
    index = [x*segment-1 for x in epoch_list]
    train_loss = [float(learner.recorder.losses[i]) for i in index]
    val_loss = learner.recorder.val_losses
    accuracy = [float(x[0]) for x in learner.recorder.metrics]
    return train_loss, val_loss,accuracy
In [19]:
# Plot loss and accuracy values 
def plot_matrix(epoch,train_loss,val_loss,accuracy):
    """
    Plot curves for trainning loss, validation loss and accuracy per epoch
    """
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax1.set_ylim([0, 1])
    epoch_list = list(range(1,epoch+1))
    ax1.plot(epoch_list,train_loss,zorder=1) 
    ax1.scatter(epoch_list, train_loss, s=10, c='b', marker="s", label='train_loss')
    ax1.plot(epoch_list,val_loss,zorder=1) 
    ax1.scatter(epoch_list,val_loss, s=10, c='r', marker="o", label='val_loss')
    ax1.plot(epoch_list,accuracy,zorder=1) 
    ax1.scatter(epoch_list,accuracy, s=10, c='g', marker="o", label='accuracy')
    plt.legend(loc='lower left');
    plt.show()
In [20]:
n_cv_round = 0
acc_val = []
epoch = 35
# Loop through each cv fold
for train_index,val_index in skf.split(df.index,df['y']):
    n_cv_round += 1
    # Load data
    data_fold = (ImageList.from_df(df,path).
                split_by_idxs(train_index,val_index).
                label_from_df().transform(tfms,size=256).
                databunch(num_workers=0,bs=bs)).normalize()
    print("This is the %d round of cross validation" %(n_cv_round))
    print("Data classes %s" %(data_fold.classes))
    print("Number of train images: %d" %(len(data_fold.train_ds)))
    print("Number of validation images: %d" %(len(data_fold.valid_ds)))
    print("Train with DarkCovidNet CNN")
    # Train model
    model = darkcovidnet_model()
    learn_fold = Learner(data_fold, model, loss_func = nn.CrossEntropyLoss(), metrics=accuracy)
    learn_fold.unfreeze()
    learn_fold.fit_one_cycle(epoch, max_lr=3e-3)
    train_loss, val_loss,accu = extract_values(data_fold,epoch,learn_fold,bs)
    plot_matrix(epoch,train_loss,val_loss,accu)
    acc_val.append(accu[-1])
    # Clean enviroment
    del learn_fold
    del model
print(acc_val)

Evaluate sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, precision, F1 score and plot confusion matrix, receiver operating characteristic¶

  • Accrucy ACC = (TP + TN) / (P + N) * 100
  • Precision PRE = TP / (TP + FP) * 100
  • Recall RC = TP/P 100 = TP/(TP + FN) 100
  • F1 = 2TP / (2TP + FP+ FN)

GoogleNet for image classification¶

Choose transfer learning model GoogleNet and Load DataBunch

In [28]:
def googlenet_model():
    """
    Construct GoogleNet transfer learnning model
    """
    # Freeze GoogleNet weights
    googlenetModel = TorchModels.googlenet(pretrained=True)
    for param in googlenetModel.parameters():
        param.requires_grad = False
    # Adjust last layer to my dataset classes
    num_ftrs = googlenetModel.fc.in_features
    googlenetModel.fc = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(data.classes))
    return googlenetModel

Conclusion¶

We applied the DarkCovidNet and GoogleNet to classify x-ray images for COVID, Normal and Viral_Pneumonia x-ray images. After training the model with 35 epochs for DarkCovidNet and 25 epochs for GoogleNet, the losses for the training and validation datasets are stable. The accuracy is ~95% for both models.

The precision,recall,f1-score and AUC score indicated both the DarkCovidNet and GoogleNet model could effectively predict the category the x-ray image belongs to. We applied 5-fold cross validation and test validation to assess the fitness of the DarkCovidNet model. The loss value is comparable between CV and test validation, we didn't observe underfitting or overfitting problem.

This notebook demonstrated the potential predictive power of deep neural networks for diagnosis of COVID-19.
